@Morten_Storvik   Basically there is a point in time when land hasn’t yet been 100% officially claimed by a population yet.  Especially when the populations of people aren’t large compared to today.  Imagine you’re watching some of the first or very early people groups fighting each other to decide who gets claim over the land.  

In that scenario there isn’t exactly a principle of “this land has been firmly established as ours—you don’t belong here!”  It’s more of the principle, “We believe in ruling this way and living as we do here.  We want to live here.  And we’ll fight to stay here and keep true to our way of life.  (Values, beliefs, etc.)”

But, there’s the unspoken acknowledgment that they’re fighting for their right to stay there and their way of life.  Not because they’re oppressed nor due to already being long established in that land necessarily.

@mkeogh76 Exactly. Or sort of, as women who can kick men's asses one way or another have actually been around as long as cinema, or even any stories in general, have been. They just used to be the exception and not seen often. Eowyn was not the only character, in renaissance poems there are Bradamante and Marfisa, there are several female warriors in folklore tales of every land, and even real historical characters (whose exploits were probably exaggerated in later stories...), and characters inspired by them have been used often enough in later fiction. Early movies had action serials with female protagonists (and the actresses often doing their own stunts even), western movies had their gun toting women, pirate movies had characters inspired by real historical female pirates like Anne Bonny and Mary Reed, and so on and so on... there are lots of those characters. But they still were the exceptions, the black swans, surprising due to their rarity among the male heroes. And probably loved simply because people love the surprising and they love underdog stories, and a woman who can physically fight trained male warriors and win fits both categories. 

Plus once upon a time hey also used to be somewhat more realistic, there was the strong impression given that there was no guarantee they would win as they would be shown to be at a disadvantage compared to men in general, just that they had the smarts and/or skills - and sometimes supernatural help - needed to compensate for their lack of strength and usually smaller size. So those physical fights they had were more exciting due to that, and their wins more satisfying because they always seemed more of a surprise. 

But now during the last decades movie makers and story tellers in general are pretending to be the inventors of those characters, and as if they were something innovative, while flooding their stories with usually very "Mary Sue" versions who tend to be overwhelmingly superior compared to the men around them, and because of that have become mostly boring and often enough thoroughly irritating because there is no suspense, no surprises, no excitement, and more often than not the characters are not only bland, they are actively irritating, people you'd probably hate if they were real and you met them because they'd come off as bullies, entitled or sometimes just plain "Karens", with not much in the way of redeeming characteristics.

@Cancoillotteman And because people like you had forgiven it, they've decided that audience needed and wanted more made-up girlbosses instead of lore-accurate characters. 

Yes, that's what Arwen was kinda turned into in the trilogy. Let's count: saves Frodo, fights off nazguls, protects Rivendell with her ultimate water magic, rebels against her father, saves Aragorn, (helps to defend Helm's Deep) - yay so she's the one who actually allowed the plot to happen, the key to everything girl! 

Still somewhat tame, because it was not 2015-2025 yet, but it opened up the can of worms.

@Tallorian why the need for the agressivity ? I stand by the fact it was a reasonable choice to have her involved in the main caracter's story early enough to endear her to the public. Once again, the mediums are different, some changes are necessary (Tom Bombadil written out stands as a good example of such).

While standing by this, I do not deny a trend that was starting to exist at the time, but like all trope it is all in the measure to reach something qualitative. You obviously reject either any change to the books when adapting them - which is unfeasible and unreasonable - or any light or positive moment enjoyed by a female caracter, which is just as unreasonable as the girlboss movement. Hence the "voice of reason", which is not necessarily mine, but necessarily a middle-ground somewhat.

If it is arrogant to state facts and refuse to adopt automatisms of judgement, then sure i am arrogant.

@f.b.l.9813 It's worse, because it created a precedent which did not exist in Tolkien's work: i.e. a romantic attraction between an elf and a dwarf. 
People who think that it doesn't matter, and if elf x human can be, then so can elf x dwarf or human x dwarf, don't understand the religious foundation of Tolkien's world building. Humans and elves are both created by Eru Iluvatar, the demiurge, as his children, gifted with sentience and purpose, and therefore could be considered somewhat related species, and canonically intermingle.

Dwarves were created as lifeless "clay dolls" by Aule, who's analogous to an archangel in Biblical terms, who tried to do creation of his own out of boredom but failed; and thus despite being granted a spark of life by Iluvatar out of compassion dwarves don't have the local version of "immortal soul" (and since Aule did his stuff ahead of Iluvatar's creation he screwed up physiology as well). To my knowledge, Tolkien never ever gave even a slightest hint that dwarves can enter into a cross-species relations with humans or elves, or that they can fall in love with each other (it's even unclear whether dwarves, as "soulless" can experience love at all), and I'm pretty sure that he would have if he wanted it to be a canon.

@Cancoillotteman You accuse me of "aggresivity" after talking down to me? Mhm, ok, I see.

And no, "reasonable choice" is not "the fact", it's your personal, _subjective_ opinion, which has to be substantiated. While "the fact" (i.e. objective observation of reality) is that Arwen did not have any prominent role in the LotR story, beside being Aragorn's love interest and a rare case of elf x human couple (she's more interesting through the lens of Silmarillion than in LotR, as a descendant of highly interesting and prominent elven bloodline), and was in no way portrayed as a warrior-princess, but she was rewritten into one for the movies. 

Why, for what purpose, and how reasonably - those are all interpretations and opinions. Mine is supported by multiple other examples of gross rewritings and making up anti-Tolkien bs by the said trio. You haven't provided any substantiation for yours so far. Wanna see how such "substantiating your opinion" looks like? Here goes: 

Yes, removal of Bombadil is one of the examples of serious rewrites, and it was a point of criticism from the fans since the Fellowship came out. However, personally I do not find it critical, and consider it a more "reasonable" change, because: 
1) the part with Bombadil would have added a lot of runtime to the already lengthy movie, so it was cut; Glorfindel's part, however, was not cut, but rather just given to Arwen; so his removal has nothing to do with "legitimate compression due to the limitations of the medium"; 
2) the fans can pretend that the Barrow-wights encounter and subsequent rescue by Bombadil happened in the movies timeline too, only outside the screen, because nothing in the story really excludes such possibility; You can't do the same with Glorfindel, since his part happened on the screen, but with another character in his place;

3) the rest of Bombadil's function (providing Dunedain-made weapons and some lore-dump) was given to Aragorn, who was already one of the key figures in the story, and quite suitable to perform it. It did not elevate him from the extremely minor character role at the expense of others, and it did not grant Aragorn any skills, traits or knowledge which he had not possessed in the book. But with Arwen it very much did. 

So no, I don't "reject any change to the books", you're trying to straw-man me. Come back when you learn how to dispute properly. Or don't, w/e.

